[2] Cholera - Taiwan (Tainan)
Date: Tue, 5 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Taiwan News [edited]
<http://www.etaiwannews.com/Taiwan/Society/2005/07/05/1120528522.htm>

DOH reports woman in Tainan may have contracted cholera
---------------------------------------------------
The Department of Health Department discovered what may be the 2nd
indigenous cholera case in Taiwan in 2005 on Mon, 4 Jul 2005, after
checking the stool of a woman who has developed symptoms of the contagious
disease.
Shih Wen-yi, deputy director of the DOH Center for Disease Control, said
that further examination is necessary before they can confirm that the
woman they found in Tainan City, southern Taiwan, has indeed contracted
cholera.
Earlier in Jul 2005, another woman in Hsinying City, Tainan County, was
confirmed to be afflicted with cholera after touching and eating what might
have been the contaminated food that she bought from a traditional market
near her home.
Shih described the 2 women who developed symptoms of cholera as separate
cases without any relation geographically or socially. The patients have
been quarantined and given proper treatment at different medical
facilities, he said. Shih also said that his center was cooperating with
the Tainan City Health Bureau in examining the patient's family members and
their living environment. Preliminary investigation shows there was no sign
of contamination.
The deputy director claimed that chances of cholera spreading in Taiwan are
small, as "most people have a good sense of sanitation" and their living
conditions are also better than those in most other countries. Shih said he
did not expect Taiwan to be proclaimed a cholera-affected area.
