[7] Cholera - Liberia
Date: Wed, 6 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica and The Analyst (Monrovia) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200507060358.html>

Cholera Threatens Liberia's Population
---------------------------------------
With the intensity of the rainy season now in Liberia, Liberians need to be
vigilant to protect themselves from the deadly and endemic disease of
cholera, which is preventable but remains a threat "especially to children
under the age of 5 -- dying from the diarrhea and dehydration cholera
causes," according to health minister Dr. Peter S. Coleman.
Speaking recently in Monrovia Dr. Coleman said that there have been
confirmed cases of cholera in Nimba and Sinoe Counties during the past 18
days. "A person may get cholera by drinking water or eating food
contaminated with the cholera bacterium. The source of the contamination is
usually the feces of an infected person. The disease can spread rapidly in
areas with inadequate treatment of sewage and drinking water, with poor
hygiene practices in too many parts of our country; cholera is a threat to
any Liberian who does not take care of their surroundings," the minister added.
The UNICEF Representative to Liberia Angela Kearney said that cholera
surveillance and data collection teams are also being strengthened,
especially in Sinoe and Nimba Counties, where recent cases of cholera have
been reported. She said that mass communication program is underway to
disseminate the information Liberians need to protect their families and
communities from this child-killing disease.
--
