[8] Cholera - Mali (Kayes)
Date: Tue, 5 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Independent Online [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=86&art_id=qw1120496580966B243>

Mali cholera outbreak claims 14 lives
-------------------------------------
An outbreak of cholera triggered by heavy rains has killed at least 14
people in western Mali since late June 2005, local authorities said on Mon,
4 Jul 2005. Residents in 3 villages in the Kayes district of the West
African country, which borders Senegal, had been told to stop using water
from the Senegal river for fear of contamination, the region's medical
officer said.
"We have confirmed 14 deaths among 110 cases of cholera," Cheikna Drame,
health director of the Kayes district, said in a statement. Health
officials were battling to stop the waterborne infection spreading further.
Africa had been free of cholera -- an intestinal infection spread by
contaminated water and food -- for more than a century, when the disease
hit western regions in 1970. It quickly spread and eventually became
endemic across most of the continent.
--
