[9] Cholera- Guinea-Bissau (Nationwide)
Date: Fri, 1 Jul 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: IRIN & Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/606a656ac16142d38fcbddcea60daadd.htm>

Over 1000 cholera cases recorded as epidemic spreads beyond capital
---------------------------------------------------
A cholera epidemic that broke out in the capital Bissau in Jun 2005 is
spreading into the interior of the country, with more than 400 new cases
reported nationwide over the past week, health officials said Fri, 1 Jul 2005.
Since the beginning of the epidemic on 11 Jun 2005, a total of 1027 cases
have been registered, including 12 deaths, said Simao Mendes, director of
Bissau's General Hospital. The hospital is struggling to cope and has more
than 300 people suffering from the water-borne disease currently crammed
into wards, he said.
Mendes said 981 of the cholera cases detected so far had occurred in the
capital, but an increasing number of people were falling sick with the
disease in other parts of this small West African country.
In the 5 days since 26 Jun 2005, 425 new cases have been reported,
including 46 outside Bissau, he said. There have been 34 cases of cholera
in Biombo region near the capital, 6 in Cacheu in the northwest, 5 in
northern Oio and 1 in Quinara in the south. 8 people have died in the
capital and 4 more in the interior, Mendes said.
Earlier, Portugal, the former colonial power in Guinea-Bissau, announced
that it was flying in 15 tons of drugs and medical equipment to help deal
with the emergency. Health Minister Odete Semedo said on Wed, 29 Jun 2005
that Lisbon was supplying rehydration fluid, disinfectant, rubber gloves
and other essential equipment.
--
